  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a clear and universal consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is widely recognized as a serious crime because it enables other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and tax evasion, to flourish by concealing the origins of the funds.\n\nMost countries have established laws and regulations to combat money laundering. For example:\n\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act are key pieces of legislation aimed at preventing and detecting money laundering.\n2. **European Union**: The EU has implemented multiple Anti-Money Laundering Directives to harmonize and strengthen measures across member states.\n3. **United Kingdom**: The UK has the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 and the Money Laundering Regulations 2017.\n4. **International Efforts**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an intergovernmental organization, sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures, which many countries adopt and implement.\n\nFailure to comply with these laws can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and reputational damage for individuals and institutions involved. Therefore, there is no ambiguity or disagreement at the legal or international level regarding the illegality of money laundering.",
